7 Sec. 472a. (1) Upon the filing of a petition under section 434
8 and a finding that an individual is a person requiring treatment,
9 the court shall issue an initial order of for involuntary mental
10 health treatment that shall must be limited in duration as follows:
11 (a) An initial order of for hospitalization shall must not
12 exceed 60 days.
13 (b) An initial order of for assisted outpatient treatment
14 shall must not exceed 180 days.
15 (c) An initial order of for combined hospitalization and
16 assisted outpatient treatment shall must not exceed 180 days. The
17 hospitalization portion of the initial order shall must not exceed
18 60 days.
19 (2) Upon the receipt of a petition under section 473 before
20 the expiration of an initial order under subsection (1) and a
21 finding that the individual continues to be a person requiring
22 treatment, the court shall issue a second order for involuntary
23 mental health treatment that shall must be limited in duration as
24 follows:
25 (a) A second order for hospitalization must not exceed 90
26 days.
27 (b) A second order for assisted outpatient treatment must not
28 exceed 1 year.
29 (c) A second order for combined hospitalization and assisted
WAM H00097'25 (H-2) mf0t8y

12
1 outpatient treatment must not exceed 1 year. The hospitalization
2 portion of the second order must not exceed 90 days.
3 (3) Upon the receipt of a petition under section 473 before
4 the expiration of a second order under subsection (2) and a finding
5 that the individual continues to be a person requiring treatment,
6 the court shall issue a continuing order for involuntary mental
7 health treatment that shall must be limited in duration as follows:
8 (a) A continuing order for hospitalization must not exceed 1
9 year.
10 (b) A continuing order for assisted outpatient treatment must
11 not exceed 1 year.
12 (c) A continuing order for combined hospitalization and
13 assisted outpatient treatment must not exceed 1 year.
14 (4) Upon the receipt of a petition under section 473 before
15 the expiration of a continuing order of for involuntary mental
16 health treatment, including a continuing order issued under section
17 485a or a 1-year order of for hospitalization issued under former
18 section 472, and a finding that the individual continues to be a
19 person requiring treatment, the court shall issue another
20 continuing order for involuntary mental health treatment as
21 provided in under subsection (3) for a period not to exceed 1 year.
22 The court shall continue to issue consecutive 1-year continuing
23 orders for involuntary mental health treatment under this section
24 until a continuing order expires without a petition having been
25 filed under section 473 or the court finds that the individual is
26 not a person requiring treatment.
27 (5) If a petition for an order of for involuntary mental
28 health treatment is not brought under section 473 at least 14 days
29 before the expiration of an order of for involuntary mental health
